I've played this game ... a lot. And it's a great party game to introduce to friends and help them clear the first level. Because clearing the first level is an ordeal. Clearing every level is an ordeal. The game is unforgiving and requires actually keeping with the rhythm, with very limited cheesing possible. Being a musician, I've actually noticed my rhythm improve. 

Besides that, let's talk about the actual game - you have to hit any key (keyboard, controller, mouse, or whatever else you can connect to your computer) when the revolving ball (planet) goes over the track. It takes some getting used to in order to understand how to 'read' it, just like it takes time to learn how to read guitar tabs or sheet music. Until you get used to reading, you should rely much more heavily on your ears and listen to the beat especially in the earlier levels. This game really is unforgiving. And for me, that's an absolute plus. It takes me back to the days where you actually had to get good or master a level or game in order to beat it. The frustration and overcoming that is required makes the reward so worthwhile. 

Once you clear the main levels there is an entire deeper world of custom levels and its own community (mostly Koreans), so be sure to join the discord and visit the forums. The people who are really into this game are... well.. REALLY into this game. That's because it has near-infinite playability. It's unbelievably cheap to buy as well, so definitely give it a try, and try to clear at least the main levels before you judge how you feel about it. If you're having a lot of trouble, take a short break and come back to it. Just like when learning a piece of music on an instrument, your brain and muscle memory adapts to it after taking a rest or getting some sleep, and you're able to play it better the next day. If you're used to rhythm games, you're already aware of this and this game is a must-try. If you're new to rhythm games, then welcome and I hope you really enjoy it as much as so many others do.

Lastly, it's 5+ years in and the community is still active, and the developers are still adding and improving the game. That shows you the kind of passion and love that surrounds this awesome game.

Having played countless rhythm games over the last 10yrs, I never expected myself to be so hooked to this one. 
  
Coming from a Bemani/VSRG background, I mainly played games that boil down to the same thing -- hit the note when it reaches the bottom of the screen. After years of clearing even the highest level charts I lost the feeling of accomplishment and thought "just another one off the checklist." Trying other games helped a bit, but at the end of the day each one was a carbon copy of the one I played before.

ADOFAI is unlike any other rhythm game I have played and gives a great feeling of accomplishment after clearing each chart. Each chart feels like a work of art and the cinematics give a huge feeling of immersion.  Yes I do get very angry at this game sometimes, but after clearing each chart I am usually able to go back to it and clear it with minimum checkpoints and even rate changes at times.
I'm on my 3rd keyboard and second desk. Rage is expensive.

Review from a veteran player that isn't just "the balls game"

This game is kind of similar to geometry dash in that once you beat the main levels, you have two choices. You can either put the game down and be content with your experience and the time you put into it.
Or you can play custom levels and end up spending hundreds of hours playing progressively more difficult custom charts just to see how much you can improve and compete with others.

Just like geometry dash, the custom levels range from slow and easy charts that only really need one or two keys to clear, to levels that can require you to be able to press up to 16 keys on your keyboard simultaneously to pass certain sections or index past 500bpm with each hand. 
Sometimes this is done well and other times it's done horribly, but it's not much of an issue because there are a variety of user created levels for just about any skill range.
Custom charts have also increased in quality dramatically over the past year since I started playing both in terms of visual appeal and charting quality.

This is for sure my favorite rhythm game and is almost my most played game on steam now because it's just incredibly satisfying to play (especially if you have a clicky keyboard). Improving at custom charts and beating ones you once couldn't is also rewarding and improving my skill is the main reason I still play. Plus It's just cool to see songs I like charted to their fullest potential in this game.

WARNING: If you do get seriously into playing custom charts, it's going to take a toll on your keyboard once things escalate in difficulty. I've only had to buy a new keyboard once because of this but that's infinity times more than with any other game. Just be careful with your kb and try not to slam the keys.

All In all I hope both I and the game continue to improve over time and I hope to see new players giving it a try and putting their accomplishments out into the community.

Disclaimer: This post is made to the noobs of rhythm games(like me!). I come from a long background of a multitude of different rhythm games (osu!, taiko, muse dash, areca, quaver) if you couldn't tell.



This game is absolutely amazing, the design is flushed out, completely bugless, no latency issues, and the charts (or maps) are stunning. Each map (or chart) is made with great care and storyboarding(background graphics) is absolutely beautiful and the best I have ever seen.
 

HOWEVER, the biggest problem I have with this game and hence this recommendation is the inability to continue if one note is missed. This gets especially frustrating on player-made charts (or maps) where the map (or chart) gimmicks catch you off-guard, forcing you to replay large sections of the chart (or map) - only to miss a note at the same exact place (then do that another 100 times). This absolutely kills the enjoyability and the artistry of the map (or chart) maker.


This post is going to fall on deaf ears as the "haters gonna hate" post on the player base and developer, but this a warning to all new players (or n00b players like me) looking to play this game.

This game is made by Ben Shapiro - facts don't care about your feelings.



Edit:
Great feedback keep them coming!

Edit 2:
Since then the developers have implemented the issues I mentioned above. Goes to show how much they care about the game.

Plays great on Steam Deck, just want to put that on the top of my review.  On the deck, you'll be hitting pretty much the ABXY buttons.  On a PC, you can use any keys on your keyboard.  You can use one finger and hit any key on the Deck or the PC keyboard.  You can also use two fingers on one hand, or a finger on both hands, and hit any keys on your Deck or PC keyboard to play this.  Doesn't matter, so long as you hit some kind of key when you need to!  Such a good thing, especially when you hit the speed rounds.

What makes this game great is that it's a very primal rhythm games.  Graphics are very minimal when you compare it to other rhythm games.  But the music and the timings that you need to hit to complete each level are supremely good.  When you finish a round, you feel like you got better at rhythm.  A lot of rhythm games are casual, you just try to finish each level and just go yay, I did it.  This game, you feel like you climbed to the peak of a high mountain.  Such a rush!

Of all the rhythm games I played - and I buy all of them on Steam because there aren't many that come out each year - this one is to me, the best of the best.  If you play any type of musical instrument, or think you're pretty good at rhythm games - this is your jam.  You need this game in your life.  It'll exercise your brain where music is concerned.

The game has 6 main levels which I completed in one sitting, then I found it has 6 more levels after that.  Then there's all these other levels you can jump to, which are extras.  Man, this game is HUGE.  Lots of levels to play, and the music is all over the place, lots of genres.  I bought the DLC the same time I got this game, I and I am nowhere near ready to get to that portion.  The main game has a LOT of levels!

This is to me, world-class rhythm gaming.  You need this game if you love rhythm games.

Oh.  One more thing.  When I played the main game, the first six levels, I was like, this is nice.  Then you can play the speed rounds of each level.  The music gets faster, and the music pitch goes higher.  That's when I realized that the music in the main game is mostly slowed down.  If you want to hear the music playing at its normal pitch and tempo, you need to play the speed rounds.  I am so addicted to playing the faster rounds JUST to hear the music playing at the right pitch and speed.  Such a great incentive to keep playing!

There's an option to play practice levels of each round, where the music is slower and you can take your time to go over the difficult parts of each song.  But honestly, it's easier when you play the speed rounds.  At least for me.

Whatever you do, if you love rhythm games, this is the ultimate.  Get it, you will love it for sure!

An excellent rhythm game for players looking for a new, unorthodox style of challenge. The base design of the game is quite elegant, and performs marvelously for the degree of precision it demands. Take heed; the difficulty of this game is no secret. For the novice rhythm gamer, it may become a frustrating exercise, and the uniqueness of the level design compared to other games in the genre can make it a challenge for more seasoned players as well. Yet, this difficulty is what makes successful level clears so extraordinarily rewarding.

Just looking at the base levels provided, there is an excellent selection of music available with well designed tutorials to get the player accustomed to the various level patterns. What truly opens the game up is the fairly expansive library of custom levels created by the community. There, one can find myriad levels ranging from simple to extraordinarily difficult, with gorgeous visuals enhancing the experience even further.

If you're up to the challenge, I highly recommend picking this up.

I would love to recommend this game, as it's pros can outweigh the cons. But there are some caveats.

Base Game with base levels as well as Muse Dash Collab, Crown Islands and Neo Cosmos have been a blast. An interesting use of rhythm and melodies that mash together really well.

As a student who finished music school I notice how much effort went into creating different forms of rhythms and polyrhythms as well. Really really cool!

But here go my caveats, almost all of them include the workshop levels.
My main issue is that difficulty ratings don't matter at all, most notably harder ones like Lorelei I almost finished at 95% with a decently low amount of effort. Meanwhile the map named "Cat Gif" I couldn't pass for 3 months, just because the rhythms felt sporadic and really poorly placed in my opinion.

My most notable issue is "Fast equals Hard" and "Can't see means hard". I currently really hate this form of difficulty, as almost 40% or more maps I couldn't finish because they give me a headache and have too many effects to even see what's happening. Most of times I had to squint to even see what was happening and what patterns were coming up.

For "Fast Equals Hard", that limitation is mostly on the hardware side. I don't think fast equals hard in music, plus it only limits based on how much carpal tunnel you want to suffer with. Because for me it demolished my will to play the game and the "Fast Equals Hard" maps. Me finishing them didn't feel good, because I would be left with wrist pain the whole day and often times it's too fast for the type of melody.

That being said (woo that was a long one), I can still appreciate and see all the efforts and cool ideas coming into play as well as the minute details of genres and different musical numbers. Frums being an awesome one (as his songs really made me interested in the game), and the art styles are really cool to see. Almost every map I played had a different art style and set piece.

So for now I would really recommend anyone to play this game, but just know when going into workshop that most maps can be hell to play. And you'll have to poke around to find a needle in a haystack.
But when you do, it can be a really cool journey~

TL/DR: Simple and challenging rhythmic fun at a low cost, but likely incredibly difficult for the rhythmically challenged.

If you have a good sense of rhythm, you'll probably love this game. It's a simple yet challenging concept with lots and lots of depth built in to keep you busy for a long time, even when disregarding all current and future DLC and custom Workshop levels. However, if you have a notably poor sense of rhythm, anything past the opening hour or two will likely be torture. The game's slow opening may demonstrate to some that this game is a teaching tool of sorts; a way to learn various different rhythmic patterns with visualizations of them. [b] This is not the case. [/b] While the game can assist with learning rhythms, it WILL have you in over your head with rhythmic complexity if you can't process rhythms quickly and effectively enough, and given the strict no-mistakes gameplay format it can be difficult to get your bearings and continue onward after a death.
For how relatively low-cost the game is compared to other rhythm games on the market, I would recommend anyone picking it up, but if you struggle with learning rhythms and/or get angry at games very easily, you might want to skip this one.

Great (and unexpectedly artistic) rhythm game. The main story has a lot more music variety which is refreshing in this landscape. Speaking of, the music score gives this sense of optimism that I grew to enjoy! You always have business left to do whenever you come back, every time with a newfound goal of further achieving perfection or chasing a new skill. No matter how long ago you finished the canon story... and its DLC.

Fire and Ice has an excellent community and 7th Beat knows it. They go out of their way to have Featured Levels in-game, which is a collection of the most popular (and artist-approved) levels that were popular in the Steam Workshop. Absolute godlike feature.

Oh yeah that's right, Fire and Ice has a sandbox editor!

With that said, one nitpick I have with custom levels is the effects/filters. Eventually you may notice filters being used everywhere. It doesn't bother me, but the repetition does pull me out of immersion at times (the variety could improve in that department).

[h1]Good-ass game. Play it.[/h1]


It's basically a rhythm game that's [i]visualized[/i] in an organic tile pattern as all the levels boil down to a path you move through made out of these tiles, with your two "orbs" rotating around an axis and you having to press any button to the beat as they go over the next tile to [b]snap[/b] onto it.
It sounds stupidly simple as-is, but the trick is that the path twists and turns and THAT twisting of the path is what gives you an organic visual hint as to [i]what timing[/i] you're supposed to have on your button presses.

Curves might make you have to hit notes on a half-beat, or [i]wait[/i] an extra half beat, or put you into offbeats for a while entirely, or even triplets and other weird stuff on diagonal twists.

...And you're gonna need to get used to that because this game gets [b]jazzy[/b] and doesn't hesitate for a SECOND to hit you with the weirdest offbeats, syncopation, triplets, quintuplets, and fucked up time signatures straight from the pits of [i]hell[/i].
It gets annoying at points, sure, but it's annoying in a Rhythm Heaven way in that it's moreso a [i]cheeky[/i] way of catching you offguard if you're not expecting it. You get used to it quickly.

You die in one miss, mind you, ala Geometry Dash, but this game [I]does[/i] have the decency of having at least one or two checkpoints in longer levels which is GREATLY appreciated.


The "base" game is only about 6 levels [spoiler](plus the bonus level after 100%ing all of the previous ones)[/spoiler] but (unsure if it was all post-release updates) there's PLENTY of postgame content after you beat that. Extra "speedup" challenges get added to every level. A whole-ass set of 6 more levels unlocks. You get an extra section or three of guest song levels, including a couple of Muse Dash crossover tracks for some reason.
Plus the semi-recent DLC that adds even [i]more[/i] stuff on top. PLUS custom levels/workshop support.

There is [b]so much[/b] stuff to this game, especially with how cheap it is. Even moreso if you find it on sale.
I [i]love[/i] rhythm games like this, that focus more on having really simple gameplay and making the [b]timing[/b] of every hit matter, as opposed to showering you with note diarrhea on a track of like 9 different buttons and calling that "difficulty".

[b]Absolutely recommended.[/b]

Before my diatribe here (and yes it is a diatribe), I want to impress upon any who may be reading this that I am a goblinoid weirdo who does not speak for everyone. Hell, I'd say I don't speak for more than half the people on the planet Earth.

I purchased the game with the intention to use its level editor. I am a human being who thinks about level editors from the moment I wake up to the moment I go to sleep. I wanted to try this game due to the mounting number of levels I have seen from this game's level editor because of this.

My time with this game so far has been short, as you can plainly see. However, in those 26 minutes, I did not find myself enjoying this game what-so-ever. I wanted to enjoy the game (trust you-me), but I found myself unable to have fun with any of the game's content.

Firstly, whilst the level editor is available from the very beginning, much of its content is locked behind in-game progress. Now, I know for a fact I don't speak for everyone, but I will say that I personally unironically believe that there is a special place in hell reserved for people who lock level editor content behind game progress. I paid for the DLC on the pretence that I'd be able to use its content in the editor from the get-go; evidently not.

"So play the game then!"

I did.

I never got past the first world.

Say "skill issue", "git gud", etc. all you want; it won't change my mind. I hate how difficult this game is, because I was more motivated to get to the level editor content. I'd generously say that I spent the first 2 minutes of the game figuring everything out (I saw a lot of this game on Youtube so I already understood the basic premise), and I'd say I spent another 2 minutes on the levels of the first world before I got to the titular level "A Dance of Fire and Ice".

I grappled with it for 22 minutes and got 70ish% of the way through, and the only thing I felt was raw, unfiltered anger and disgust. I'd most closely describe it as the video game equivalent of being body-checked repeatedly by an overweight, oversized cut of raw chicken. Just anger, disgust, and general distaste. Not even anticipation or excitement for getting closer to the end, it was just an angry feeling. I felt throughout as though reaching the end of the level was not going to garner a reaction of "Hurray! I did it", but rather a reaction of "Now give me my editor content f*ckface".

Again, and I cannot stress this enough, I cannot speak for everyone. Not everyone is a creation-obsessed freak of nature like I am. But I got nothing out of this game except genuine vitriol. Buy only if you unironically enjoy Geometry Dash.

The minesweeper secret was more fun than the actual game content.

TL;DR: Buy if you like Geometry Dash. Game locks its level editor content behind its game content and I'm the only sick freak who cares.

I haven't played many rhythm games in my life, but this one definitely ranks near, if not the top.

The premise of the game is exceptionally straightforward. You play as 2 orbiting planets where your objective is to align them with each tile in a chart in an orderly orbiting fashion from start to finish, to the rhythm of the music. While mistakes are allowed to be made, they are usually hard to recover from, and consecutive ones will result in a Game Over. Simple, yet challenging.

The game offers 12 base worlds, with additional, more difficult ones to unlock later by completing said worlds. Through the Steam Workshop, players can also play and share their very own user-made charts, with virtually any song to grasp, as long as they deem to be fit by the artist.
The charts that the player has to go through present different patterns such as long, triangular-shaped, overlapping zig-zag roads and otherworldly designs that the developers could think of. Throughout each world, the backdrop, visuals, and music change accordingly, making each course unique and varied.

My only complaint about this game sometimes is the way the practice system is handled. Practice allows you to replay specific sections of a chart at different speeds to help you understand the pattern, and this is great, but the problem is that it requires you to pass it *first* in order to do so, which defeats the whole purpose of practice. This results in a lot of unnecessary trial and error, which is quite infuriating at times, especially when the tiles start to overlap and get increasingly more difficult to read in the harder stages of the game.

I am 42.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and adopted our son together. They are now both 4 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I found myself lost and miserable. I was self destructive. I got so mad one day from everything spiraling out of my control that I punched some concrete in a moment of overwhelming emotion. That caused me to break my 5th metacarpal in my right hand... my working hand... my games hand.. the hand that I held and carried my children to bed with.. The hand I desperately needed to make sure I could continue to provide.

After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 ♥♥♥♥ing minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

After coming to that realization, I turned the game off, and I went back to work. It hurt my hand like hell but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so damn sorry for myself, and I became the father I needed to be in that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving as.

Today, I am close friend with my kids mother. We don't fight, or argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents, and friends.

I now have 3 kids. My third child is, wait for it, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my own separation, and we just stumbled in to each others life unexpectedly. We have been in a relationship for a year now, and are very happy together.

Moral of the story, you never know what life holds in store for you, and if I would have given up when all the odds were stacked against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

That's all, thank you.

Beautiful and unique rhythm game that unlike other games in this genre, is [i]insanely simple and easy to get into.[/i] Music is great and tracks range from very easy to pretty difficult ([spoiler][b]Crown Island levels[/b][/spoiler]), although they don't come even close to the difficulty that custom levels can have. 
The ability to create custom levels is probably the best addition to this game because it's basically [b][i]infinite replayability[/i][/b] and allows for amazing, creative levels to be made. It's also what keeps this game alive, which is how games like Geometry Dash and osu! survive.
For anyone scrolling through the reviews before buying, I highly recommend playing this game especially if you enjoy rhythm games like me. I also recommend playing 7th Beat Games' other game, Rhythm Doctor. It is amazing, and possibly even better than ADOFAI.

TL;DR probably one of the best rhythm games for beginners, has custom level support, buy now now now now now

This is one of the best (in my opinion) rhythm games out there. A Dance Of Fire And Ice (ADOFAI) is easy to learn but hard to master game. You can play with the mouse or the entire keyboard or both, there is no limit. The base 12 worlds are very begginer friendly and the bonus levels are hard and fun. The game also has a DLC which in my oppinion is worth buying.

  And I haven't gotten to the best part which is the community made levels. If you don't like the levels which the developers have made you can still find levels made by users. Did I mention YOU can make the levels? It's true! The editor is very simple and easy to understand but if you have trouble don't hesitate to look up tutorials.

  So in conclusion the game is simple but hard. It's main 12 levels are fun and the bonus levels are challenging and hard. If you think this game is right for you buy it!!! But if you think you can't handle the difficulty don't worry there's plenty of fish in the sea.

Really fun! I like how visual the rhythm is, with the tile's angles and different shapes, you can really understand it just by looking at the map, which is really refreshing-  most games like this get overly complicated, and you can't really tell with what part of the song the button is in sync with. I found it really refreshing for this not to be an issue in this game! 
The maps and songs are pretty cool as well, and I like that they make you practice the moves in small snippets before having to play for a whole song- each mechanism is thoroughly shown to you, which works in the game's advantage with how complicated it gets in the later stages, especially after you start playing around with community-built stages. Some of the names for the tutorial stages are pretty funny as well :] And of course, the training mode has proven to be really really useful, especially since it allows you to slow down the song in order to actually learn the song's rhythm instead of pushing buttons at random until you get it right.
Overall 100% would recommend, the only real flaw is the instant-kill which gets just a bit annoying when stuck on a section (although I can't blame the game for being difficult), and I've found it a bit difficult to switch to multi-button playing once the game requires you to up the speed- it would be a bit better if it got you used to playing with multiple buttons from the beginning. Other than that, really cool, both visually and soundwise, and super fun gameplay if you like a good challenge!

The base game contains hours upon hours of fun content, and has difficulties to fit the needs of almost all players. Final verdict: 8.5 [Very Good]

This game is pretty good, I'll segment some of my feelings about it

Playing the game by itself - Eh
It should be great if you are new to rhythm games, but those like me who try tens of rhythm games might learn too quickly, the extra islands can only stave off hunger for more levels for so long. the base levels teach you enough to get going on most easy maps, the only problem i see is that the music isnt to my taste most of the time ("It Go" is awesome)

Playing online, you have access to tons of maps but because of the gameplay it falls into something that isnt quite spectacular--
Memorization! if you want to play anything much more difficult than the base game levels you will have to memorize a lot of the songs, all normal rhythm game songs like kobaryo, camellia, etc. will be too fast for normal play if you map it like other games, making it require memorization (luckily, there is a practice mode for this)

the gameplay, i really love it, you hit any button on your keyboard or mouse (within reason) and it will make the ball go to the next note! if you miss a note once then you die, if you hit too early then its fine as long as you hit at the right time when its time, luckily most maps in this game are synced pretty well if you go for the popular ones, or if you find one on youtube you like
if you get this game, make sure to sync properly to your headset, if you feel like the notes are appearing before the sound in your headphones then make sure to fix it

I randomly bought this game today just because it looked like just another cool rhythm game, but it made me reconnect with my younger self in the sense of how hard I was trying. When I was younger I would be the kid sweating at everything he did, literally everything. I always asked the dumb questions just so I could really grasp what I was learning.

This game made me remember, its ok to be the one sweating at something that should be easy but is harder for you, its ok to be the one who asks the dumb questions just so he can understand the concept better, its ok to fail and fail and fail, because as long as you keep going no matter how long it takes you will reach your goal. Even if you get made fun of for being bad at something that everyone else is better than you at, as long as you put in 110% you will reach your goal and go farther than most.

Do you want a REAL rhythm game? 

Isn't it weird that as a musician, a drummer at that, I've rarely ever found interest in rhythm games?
The reason is that most commonly, music games are more about reaction time and button mashing rather that understanding and keeping the music and the rhythm.

This is different in ADoFaI, you have to rely on and train your rhythm skills.  You have to hit every beat in the level if you want to progress, which is hard if your rhythm isn't well trained, but that's what the game is for! You might actually get better as a musician if you play this game, since the music is visualised in tiles that are actually quite reminiscent of sheet music! Plus, it's a lot of fun (unlike sheet music lol)

The tutorials are really well designed, they teach you the basics song by song, and once you're done with the base game you can hop over and try your hand at the tough bonus levels and custom levels made by the community, some of which insanely difficult, but the addicting nature of the game makes me not want to stop trying!! Big recommendation by me!

I really love this game, it has loads of official content, and the online levels to keep you busy. Updates come frequently, events happen often, and the community is very busy. I've read some of the reviews to this game, but I noticed, that some of the bad reviews don't make any sense, or I can't find a reason to. Some people keep saying that the game is offbeat, which is totally normal. You can fix this by going into settings and going into audio and pressing c which then it will send you to the calibration page. Other people say that the game is too hard, with 6-X being the common reason why. That's just cause you're bad at the game or don't have enough patience to loose and start over. That's one of the main points of A Dance of Fire and Ice. It's supposed to make you fail, until you memorize it enough to pass. Another common denominator I saw was that people were complaining straightly about how garbage the game was, and how it was garbage. Now I can understand this, but not when they have literally like 0.2 hours of playtime. They probably didn't even reach world 2 before giving up and saying that this game was very bad. Another reason is that people say that you can get very angry at this game. I can understand this as well, since I also had times when I felt frustrated, but really, you just need to take a 5 minute break and do something else. If you can't do that, maybe rhythm games aren't for you, since most of them rely heavily on memory. I really love this game, and I even recommended this game to many of my friends who don't even enjoy the rhythm game genre, but they loved this as well, having dozens of hours on it.

There are plenty of amazing looking levels built by the community too, although I don't touch too many of those. As a casual music rhythm gamer, a lot of the featured levels just aren't for me. Lucky for me, a good level doesn't mean it must be a difficult level. There are plenty of good levels here... and difficult levels too! Either way, you'll have a LOT of fun with this game, there's something for everyone.

The Neo Cosmos DLC is ALSO super solid and is also worth the price. It only includes 5 main levels but they are all incredibly creative.

--Review-- It's a fun game for players like me, Who enjoy rhythm games, And i'm starting to get used to the features! (Examples: Twirls, Speed Changes, triple planets, planet radius, freeroams, etc.)

Painfully addictive. Ultimately this game is still kinda a baby so there's a lot of places where it could be improved, such as an Osu-esque timeline in the editor to make building less complicated, an in-game verification system a la Geometry Dash so you don't have to reference the forum to find passable levels, and replacing the in-game difficulty with the forum difficulty so it's not entirely self-assigned. But if you're a Geometry Dash player who's sick of the unsynced levels and excessive focus on decoration over gameplay (like I was), here's a game like that which actually cares about rhythm.

For its price, ADoFaI is an absolute steal. People complain about it being frustrating how you have to start over when you miss a note, but in the longer campaign songs there are checkpoints often enough that it is just a matter of you learning the rhythm vocabulary thoroughly. 

And then there are people who complain about how because when you miss a note you die instantly, it makes custom map excruciatingly frustrating. This is a lame excuse of a review, because every custom map is made and published to the creator's discretion, so you should be getting the experience that they intended, whether that be frustrating or not.

The campaign is well worth over the $5.99 USD that I spent, and player made levels should serve as icing on the cake for players who want to get really into pushing their limits, so I literally cannot sympathize with any of the negative reviews I've seen.

A Dance of Fire and Ice is a mesmerizing rhythm-based game that blends simplicity with complexity, offering a unique and challenging gameplay experience. The game's minimalistic visuals and elegant design create a visually stunning and immersive world. Each level presents a rhythmic puzzle that requires precision and timing to navigate through intricate patterns. The intuitive controls allow for seamless movement, adding to the fluidity of gameplay. 

The music is a key element, with dynamic and rhythmic tracks that synchronize perfectly with the gameplay, enhancing the overall experience. The difficulty curve is well-balanced, gradually introducing new mechanics and increasing the challenge. The game's replayability is high, as each level encourages mastery and improvement. The satisfaction of successfully completing a level is immensely rewarding. A Dance of Fire and Ice is a captivating and addictive game that combines rhythmic gameplay, striking visuals, and an immersive musical experience.

After playing this game on and off for the past two years, I can confidently say that this is the best rhythm game I've played. The irony is that it might be the most simplistic rhythm game with you only needing one or two keys to beat the main levels the game has to offer. This is a game that isn't necessarily about reaction time like in most rhythm games but rather learning the often complex and varied rhythms that can be found in each level and the custom levels use this to create difficult levels with rhythms that become incredibly satisfying to master once you've learnt them. 

If you are limiting yourself to the main levels created for the game, you are missing out on a huge catalogue of incredible levels that really stretch the mechanics of this game to their limit. By allowing the player to use any key on the keyboard to the play the game, custom levels can utilise up to 8 button gameplay to really test the player's ability to play extremely fast and complex rhythms. Over 200 hours in, I have just started to get good at alternating with four keys and I know I can continue to push my skills as I have never felt like I hit a wall in this game unlike with other rhythm games. 

Overall if you enjoy rhythm games, the is an absolute must and I would highly recommend you explore what the community has created in this game, even if the steam workshop isn't always the most intuitive to browse.

This is one of my favorite rhythm games ever, heck, one of my favorit games. Though I think the game was great from the start, the updates and support it has gotten over the years really shaped it to what I think is the perfect rhythm game. Don't get me wrong, the game is not perfect, but I do think its concept makes for the best rhythem gameplay when done right, and lately it's been done very right, by both the devs themselves and the comunity. The game allowes you to visualize different rhythms in a way that no other game does, and some songs really make that concept shine, especially those with polyrhythms, odd time signitures, or antrhing to do with the rhythm of the song. For that reason, I think that this game could be an excelent first rhythm game for anyone, despite its difficulty. From my experience, the game doesn't really drop in price that much at sales, you might as well just buy it at full price, which is really not a lot. I really hope this game and its comunity stay as great as they are now.

Gameplay and Mechanics:
A Dance of Fire and Ice introduces a novel approach to the rhythm game genre, providing players with a simple yet innovative gameplay mechanic. The game revolves around guiding a shape along a path that corresponds to the beat of the music. Players must time their actions carefully, pressing or holding the corresponding input at precise moments, to navigate the obstacles and progress through the levels.

The mechanics in A Dance of Fire and Ice are elegantly designed, requiring a delicate balance between timing, reflexes, and spatial awareness. The gameplay gradually increases in complexity, introducing new elements and patterns that demand quick thinking and precise execution. The intuitive controls and responsive feedback ensure a satisfying and immersive rhythmic experience.

Audiovisual Presentation:
A Dance of Fire and Ice captivates players with its minimalist art style and mesmerizing audiovisual presentation. The visuals are sleek and understated, featuring abstract shapes and vibrant colors that complement the rhythmic gameplay. The minimalist approach allows players to focus on the core gameplay mechanics while still offering a visually striking experience.

The game's soundtrack is a standout feature, with a diverse selection of electronic and ambient music that perfectly matches the gameplay and sets the tone for each level. The music evolves dynamically as players progress, syncing seamlessly with the obstacles and enhancing the immersion. The combination of the pulsating beats, synchronized visuals, and responsive gameplay creates a synergistic and immersive audiovisual experience.

Level Design and Replayability:
A Dance of Fire and Ice offers a wide array of meticulously designed levels, each with its own unique challenges and musical compositions. The level design strikes a balance between accessibility and difficulty, allowing players to progress at their own pace while also offering more challenging levels for those seeking mastery.

The game's replayability is a notable strength, as players can strive for higher scores and perfect their performance in each level. The inclusion of a leaderboard and the ability to unlock additional songs and content adds to the game's longevity, ensuring that players will find themselves returning to the dancefloor time and again.

Conclusion:
A Dance of Fire and Ice delivers a captivating and immersive rhythmic experience. With its innovative gameplay mechanics, minimalist art style, and mesmerizing music, the game stands out in the rhythm genre. The precise controls, responsive feedback, and intuitive level design make for a satisfying and engaging gameplay experience.

The audiovisual presentation in A Dance of Fire and Ice is a true highlight, immersing players in a visually striking world of abstract shapes and vibrant colors, all synchronized to an eclectic soundtrack. The game's replayability and the pursuit of mastery provide an incentive for players to continue dancing to the rhythm.

For fans of rhythm games and those seeking a unique and immersive musical experience, A Dance of Fire and Ice is a must-play. Its innovative gameplay mechanics, audiovisual presentation, and captivating level design make it a standout title in the genre, offering a mesmerizing dance with fire and ice.

[h1] RAGE SPHERES. [/h1]

A Dance of Fire and Ice, henceforth referred to as ADOFAI, is a "one-button" rhythm game. You tap Space. (Or whatever else you want, all inputs are equivalent.) That's it. (OK there's *one* official level that does require 2 simultaneous inputs, but it's kind of a throwaway, so don't worry about it.)

But how it keeps itself from being boring, as I think you can tell, is by its unique visualization of rhythm. The time until the next note is dictated by rotational distance, rather than lateral distance. (It go spinny.) This is hard to get your head around, especially when one miss sends you right back to the beginning of the level (or checkpoint, for longer ones, *thankfully!*)

ADOFAI is a hard game. Rhythm gamers are certainly familiar with the feeling of trying to get a full combo or other precision-based achievement and walking an absolute razor's edge with their nerves near the end of a level, but then getting a RUSH once you finally manage it. ADOFAI distills that entire experience, frustration and elation alike, into its entire experience.

It's goddamn addicting.

The full setlist of this game isn't very long, not more than a half hour, but because of the high demand of the game, you can easily sink double-digit hours in before you've even unlocked the whole main game, not even counting the Crown Island or the excellent Neo Cosmos DLC. It's amazing how high the game can take its own skill ceiling for being a "one-button" game. Once you're on the back of its skill floor, it just keeps going up, it doesn't stop.

There is so much game here for so little coin, and it's made by developers who are veterans of the rhythm game scene and genuinely care about it. While some of the early tracks are a bit rough (albeit charming in their own right), the whole back half is banger after banger, and of course there's first-class mod support and its editor was just recently overhauled with new features so customs are about to start popping off yet again.

I can hardly recommend this game enough. You'll hate it, and then you'll love it, and then you'll hate it again. But it'll always be there, ready for you to take another stab at it.

It's not a bad game, but there is one decision that makes me have to recommend against it.  If you miss a note late, you have to restart the entire song (some songs have checkpoints but most do not).  While the practice mode is a godsend and makes harder sections actually beatable, it is not fun to be 2 minutes into a song, miss a single note late by 1/8th a beat, then have to start the entire thing over again.  You can be early without instantly failing also, so it encourages you to not actually learn the hard parts, and instead just press the button at whatever the highest tempo part is at any given section to ensure that you pass it.  The unforgiving late/miss mechanic combined with long restarts mean I can't recommend any of my friends play the game.  Go play Rhythm Doctor instead, same devs, doesn't punish you brutally for a missed note.

A dance of fire and ice is an exceptionally captivating rhythm game that truly stands out. From its meticulously crafted game mechanics to its mesmerizing sound design, every aspect is expertly executed. The main game levels strike a perfect balance, providing an ample challenge without overwhelming players and dampening their enthusiasm. The gratification of hitting keys in perfect synchrony with the beat is immensely satisfying, enhanced by the captivating artistry and stunning visual effects.

DLC is an absolute gem, definitely worth investing in. In addition to introducing new maps to explore and conquer, it boasts a compact yet enthralling storyline that adds depth to the gaming experience. Moreover, the built-in editor offers an array of versatile functions, effects, and options, empowering players to create their own unique and personalized maps.

Kudos to the developers for their exceptional work on A dance of fire and ice. They have truly crafted a masterpiece that not only captivates players but also showcases their dedication and talent.

The game's simple yet visually striking graphics and atmospheric soundtrack create an immersive experience that draws you in. However, don't be fooled by the game's simplicity - it can be deceptively challenging, requiring a lot of focus, coordination, and practice to master. Personally, I have not been able to beat all the levels yet, but that hasn't diminished my enjoyment of the game. Every time I play, I feel myself getting a little better, and the feeling of accomplishment when I finally get past a particularly difficult section is incredibly satisfying. If you're looking for a challenging yet enjoyable game that will keep you coming back for more, A Dance of Fire and Ice is definitely worth checking out.

Have you ever thought to yourself, "What if Guitar Hero and Dance Dance Revolution had a baby, and that baby was locked in a dungeon with nothing but a metronome and suicidal tendencies?" Probably not. But buckle up anyhow buttercup, because the Overseer of the Neo Cosmos is here to slap your ass.

This game is the embodiment of the phrase "easy to learn, hard to master." It's like being waterboarded by a rhythm game, but in a good way. 

You press one button, and that's it. The controls are as simple and easy as a drunken one-night stand with your ex - minimal effort, maximum regret, and questionable satisfaction.

The visuals are as minimalist as a vegan's grocery list, but with a soundtrack that'll make vibe like a 17th-century bard on speed. Your ears will be the main stars here, so make sure to have those bad boys primed and ready for action.

As you progress, the game will start to treat you like a rhythmically challenged chimp as your fingers stumble through the minefield of beats, but when you nail it, you'll feel like you just got extra credit on the chromosome test. 

Overall, A Dance of Fire and Ice is a gem. It'll remind you that life is an endless cycle of pain, joy, and funky beats. The game is a journey of musical masochism that's as enjoyable as it is brutal. You won't regret it. 

10/10, would dance with fire and ice again.

Most frustrating game I have ever played. Seriously, I had to move other F-tier games UP on my games enjoyment tierlist because they didn’t deserve to be as low as this game.

In rhythm games, the way to create fluid gameplay is having patterns that players can sightread with their brain on autopilot, rather than having to overthink while playing. This game does the exact opposite of that; you have to consciously think about every single input, even when there are 5+ of them a second with brutally unforgiving timings. In some maps, the notes are almost entirely syncopated, making it even more difficult to sightread. Every level has about 7 tutorials ahead of it to teach you all the stupid patterns before throwing them at you 3 times faster all in a row and hoping you remember them, if that’s any indication of how unintuitive the gameplay is.

Additionally, sometimes all the different shaped patterns got so confusing that it was legitimately easier to play with my eyes closed than try to follow along with the visuals. You’ll often find 3 or 4 notes stacked on top of each other so that you basically just have to guess when to hit in order to syncopate the way the game wants you to.

The game will give you “hints” if you’re failing a lot—but the only two things it ever says to do are “practice” and “try using two hands,” which is pretty demeaning once you’re 40 hours into the game and it’s saying “oh, did you know that practicing will help you get better?” especially since the practice mode doesn’t even let you play past the farthest point you’ve gotten to in the level. Also, using two hands, which seems to be the meta for harder custom levels in this game, requires you to think even more about every single input you make. I finally managed to get the hang of it a little bit on the Final Hope speed trial (the very last one I did), but for new players, it’s not at all intuitive.

Oh, and on top of all that, you can’t miss A SINGLE NOTE or you fail.

In the 40 hours I played of this game, I did not ONCE feel like I was having fun, other than playing some of the “minigames” in T3-X, one of the DLC levels that has some actually creative applications of the game’s concept [spoiler]like shooting asteroids to the beat[/spoiler]. However, I think it’s pretty telling that the only time I ever had fun playing ADOFAI was on the level that least resembles ADOFAI. The DLC is also a little overpriced for offering just 5 maps (with a slight remixed version for 4 of them, but still) at almost the price of the full game.

Anyway, this is legitimately the worst experience I’ve ever had playing a videogame. I never plan to touch it again.

here's my experience from beginning to completing all achievements. the mechanics are easy to learn, but the game still manages to bring challenge with different kinds of patterns, some more challenging. I found some of the main levels to be rather difficult at first, but once you get to the rhythm, even a hard level is enjoyable to play

as for the DLC, the main levels are fun, I had a lot of fun learning the new mechanics, however the EX worlds turned out to be much more difficult. which isn't that big of an problem, other than the occasional flood of emotions as you die right next to a checkpoint over and over again. 

another good thing about the game is the level editor and custom levels. I have not looked thoroughly into the custom levels section but the ability to make your own levels and share them to the world adds so much more to do. anyways, that is where I will be going now that my review is done

I have just over 300 hours in this game and I'm still nowhere near the pros, normally with any other game I would've stopped trying long before I hit 100 hours, but the satisfaction you get from beating you're hardest song is so overwhelming and amazing. It was definitely more frustrating starting off but at the same time it was addicting, I was mad but I knew I was so close to beating the level, and when I would, I'd just pop off and go crazy. This is a mutual feeling for anyone that has had to grind a song over 1000 times like me, but the feeling is just insane. If you're dedicated and not someone who just gives up because it's "hard" this is, in my opinion, the best rhythm game on the market.

A Dance of Fire and Ice is a rhythm game like no other. Sure, you have classics like Osu! and Etterna, but the dynamic of ADOFAI is rather unique and interesting. I love this game for a couple reasons, you can see how the game grew as you play and how out of the ordinary the mechanics are is simply outstanding to me. Often times you'd think that following a pattern on a rhythm game would be pretty straight-forward for the most part but that is not the case with ADOFAI. I have had multiple instances where I had to attempt a pattern multiple times to even fathom what was happening, and I've played rhythm games pretty much my entire life. The DLC is really great too, the levels are fun, and the visuals are a step above from what previously seen on the base game. Overall, A Dance of Fire and Ice is a spectacular rhythm game and a really worthy purchase. I definitely recommend this game!!

One of my favorite rhythm games, incredibly addicting and just as rewarding.

If you play Geometry Dash and love rhythm games, absolutely try this out. The restart on each failed attempt should feel relatively normal and you already know the satisfaction that comes with completing a level after hundreds or even thousands of attempts. The skill ceiling is incredibly high as well, and the same kind of skill progression that can be felt in GD is present in this game.

If you don't play GD but are still an avid rhythm game enjoyer I'd recommend trying out the itch.io demo before picking it up. Keep in mind that although the gameplay is fundamentally the same the game has gotten countless updates since then and both looks and plays far better than it does on itch. If you like what you see then why not try it out, the price is more than reasonable.

I think the main pull of this game for me was just how intuitive it is. There is no "how to play" tutorial because you don't need one; anyone can look at this game and figure out exactly how it works. The music is incredible, the levels are filled with creativity and cool gameplay concepts, and the game does a great job of easing you into each new rhythmic pattern without holding your hand. The level editor allows for so much ingenuity that the greater community has built incredible levels, even forming teams to create mind-blowing stuff. I can honestly say that I was hooked from the first time I opened this game.  While ADOFAI is branded as a "one button rhythm game" the difficulty increases as you move on through the levels and gets pretty insane in Neo Cosmos as well (though you can still get by with two fingers).  The community levels also show how great the, well, community is, too.  

As for the gameplay itself, the way you play is by tapping rhythms in the form of tiles as two balls orbit each other travel with one stopping on a tile at a time as the other swings around to the front and each tap being a step on said tile that can make up shapes that correspond to anything from simple straight notes to rather complex rhythms.  This makes for an incredibly enjoyable experience, not to mention visually appealing making it unlike any other rhythm game that I can think of anyways.  ADOFAI is a strict game in the sense where if you miss a single tile you need to restart either from the beginning or a checkpoint (if there is one) with some fudge factors of early and late taps and the ability to overtap as well (but not too many time else you fail with this too).  
      >>There is also a practice mode where you select where in each song to start and end and to change the tempo by %.

While this can be seen as a hardcore rhythm game, it feels more of an experience that you can see quite explicitly how you grow as you play each level.  For example, even coming from years of Osu! and Muse Dash, it was fun yet pretty awkward to play at first, especially getting used to shapes for rhythms rather than something from any other rhythm games out there, but soon enough I was able to do quite well with the most difficult map I've completed being Meganeko - Moonlight Sonata 3rd Movement Remix (Mapped by Ssmille).

If anyone likes rhythm games, this is definitely one to pick up because it can become addictive pretty quickly, not to mention it almost feels underpriced with how much playtime you can get out of it!

It's a tough call on my recommendation, but in the end, I don't think I'd recommend it.

The game's big concept is that you move along a path to rhythm of the music.  For the most part, this works as intended pretty well.

These are the parts that combine to a frustrating experience.
1.  You need to sight read the path to progress.
2.  You lose in a single mistake.
3.  The game actively messes with your ability to view the path, and your character.

When parts of the path overlap, it quickly becomes a major hassle to try and work out the rhythm, and on top of that, the game might do things like spin the camera, hide the path, change the upcoming path, zoom in/out, focus the camera in a specific spot instead of following, etc.

As a player, the solution is to follow the rhythm, but since you lose on a single failure, thats very difficult.  There is a practice mode, but it doesn't let you go more than a couple seconds further into a song that you've already reached normally.  When you get stuck at a certain part, you need to break out practice mode, then go back to main mode, hopefully beat it, and if you get stuck again, it's back to practice mode for a small section, and so on.  In the end, this is a secondary issue though.

At the core of my review, I get frustrated when the game wants me to enjoy it's fun path to rhythm gameplay, but then messes with the visuals so you can't really do that anymore.

EDIT:  I changed my review to positive, because despite the parts I don't like, and that I find them frustrating, I don't think it's fair to say it's not recommended.  In the end, it's a fun game, but not without negative aspects.

After doing almost everything the main game has to offerc, I have to say that this is one of the most unique,sick and fun rythm games I've tried. The patterns on different worlds may appear to be easy to get the hang of however the game always finds new ways and mechanics to throw at you. I recommend this to everybody even if you aren't keen on rythm games as this one is very easy to get the hang of.

Many rhythm games, while great on their own, tend to have a few fundamental flaws in them, but A Dance of Fire and Ice steers away from them.

Whenever you're playing a rhythm game, you usually will eventually run into a song where it introduces a new pattern in the middle of a song, and you will ultimately fail said pattern because you just have no clue how to approach it in the two seconds that it shows up on screen. This either results in you failing the song, having to restart the song and play it for two minutes, or you just barely scraping through, making you feel like you didn't really need to learn that pattern. Of course, you could go into practice mode and pick that segment, but that kicks you out of the flow state.

A Dance of Fire and Ice handles this differently: every world starts with introductory songs that are meant for solely learning new (or sometimes relearning old) patterns before giving you the actual challenge of the world. While the gameplay itself might feel harsh by ending the song immediately after one failure, you never feel overwhelmed by it, since you have just been taught how to handle the patterns. The game does not dwell on your failure, and you are quickly back at it again.

Another minor thing to praise about is that the game does not rely on visual trickery for its rhythm gameplay. Many modern rhythm games (especially the one-button kinds like Geometry Dash) like to make confusing visuals in order to make timings harder, which in my opinion takes the rhythm out of rhythm games. While the snaking pattern of the tiles might seem like it's designed to confuse you, you quickly understand the patterns of it and the snakiness becomes clarifying.

As for the songs, there's a neat selection of custom songs. My favorite one is this Katamari Damacy style upbeat, happy song (10-X), which just took the frustration away while failing over and over again.

Ultimately, it's a bit on the short end for the baselines, but for $5, you could do a whole lot worse. The Steam Workshop has plenty of custom maps for the game, so you won't run out of content.

A little dissapointed... is a rhythm game but at the same time it is not. You can predict the beat  asked (moment to press the button) by memorizating the distinct road patterns presented in the levels or by learning the melody, there is not audible cues as others rhythm games, the road is the preview of what is coming next.

For example, if the road is a straigh line you only press the button with the tempo of the song.  If you are entering from the top and the patter is a flipped "C" your beat must be slower; if it is a "C" you beat must be is faster. If you are entering this patterns from below, the rules invert.

Then you can get combinations like a "S" o flipped "S", or different rotations of an "L". Memorizce the type of beat requiered for each form, and when you see it, prepare for it and execute it according with the tempo of the song. 

If it is to much for you memorice, you can only use the rule "if i go right i must go a little slower, if go left a little faster".

The game could be more enjoyable if it was not requiered to not miss a single beat for hearing all the song. There is not an option to play the song entirely and see how good you did in the run. There is a practice option, but you can only practice until you reach highest progressión point in the song.

Having put nearly two hundred hours into this game since I got it in March of 2022, I think I can conclude that I really like this game.

A Dance of Fire and Ice is a good entry point for people who already play video games or have a background in music to dive into the world of rhythm gaming, but not one for absolute beginners. 

This game is fair both in how it teaches you to do the dance and its way of notating music. If you're no good at pattern recognition this game might help you to learn it because It's very unforgiving compared with other games of the genre. One major mistake - one dropped input and you're done with only the occasional checkpoint to keep the frustration from getting out of hand. The game is elegant in its simplicity but it gets hard pretty quickly.

Persevere though... clear the sixth, the twelfth and bonus world and you'll see just how shiny of a gem the game is. Then get the DLC because Neo Cosmos slaps and play customs.

This game is a ton of fun! Unlike other rhythm games this one demands perfection out of every note right out of the gate. I feel like I am learning how to play the song rather than just getting through it. The practice menu helps a lot with mastering those difficult runs. There's a small base track selection, but that has been beefed up with colabs as well as the recent DLC. Once you are finish with that time to hit the community tracks, where we switch to tough but fair difficulty to just plain nonsense. Finally, it can run on fairly low hardware settings. If you like Rhythm games, this is an excellent addition to your roster.

Edit: I cannot recommend buying the DLC. The fun in rhythm games for me is in learning to play the beats correctly. The DLC leans heavily into making it more difficult to tell what you are supposed to play even is by either hiding the track entirely or deliberately arranging the notes to make it more difficult to see what is going on. It feels like I am trying to read sheet music with a 3 year old constantly tearing the page out from in front if me. I'm happy to learn to handle difficult patterns, I am not okay with being told to play patterns I am not allowed to see. Stick with the base game to learn and then focus on the more challenging community made content after.

The original levels included are fun and teach you the basics of the game. Some tracks weren't my favourite, genre wise, but those I liked were grinded out by a lot, even after I've completed them.

The best part in my opinion is the Steam Workshop feature. It's where I spend almost all the time if I boot up the game. People are putting a lot of work in it and the community is both helpful and motivated to bring their favourite songs into the workshop with interesting mechanics. It's a lot of fun finding new levels and challenges which show you how good you can get. Be careful though, the community levels can be pretty hard in the beginning. I genuinely think [i]A Dance of Fire and Ice[/i] is rhythm game perfection. The game expresses rhythms in angles, leading to the incredibly unique visualization of complex rhythms. Since quarter notes are straight lines (180°), a triplet is created by making three 60° angles, which makes, you guessed it, a triangle. [i](super cool stuff)[/i] Of course, all this cool mathematical rhythm stuff wouldn't be fun without good music, and [i]A Dance of Fire and Ice[/i] delivers excellent tracks with a large variety of styles. [i](Whereas many rhythm games fall short of the variety part.)[/i]

[b]I highly recommend this game if you like challenging rhythm games.[/b]

It is a very good game for people who like rhythm games e.g. osu or project sekai, I would actually recommend it because its very easy to time, once you get the hold of the game and whats its about. People who have played for over a year can probably do songs like Kurokotei - Chronostasis which is a VERY hard song in my opinion, and I would not recommend that song for new people as it could make you rage as you don't know how to time those beats at the start. In my opinion, it is one of the best games which can help timing. Another thing which makes me say its one of the best is that you cannot get too many earlys in a timespan and not get a late [Making you lose] It is very complicated the further in [Number]-x as its meant to train you at the start, and see how that helps by making each one harder and harder, as i have only played for 31 hours, I am not as good as you think. What I don't like is that  Lenient mode doesn't help, just makes it more challenging for me, this isn't a bug though, its just something that happens on some occasions. You do not need to make any modifications to the game, I will maybe use Normal mode for most fast songs, as I like to challenge myself. By the way, if you read this until here, congrats! Now back to the review, my most favourite part of this game is that there is many different workshop levels to try out in Workshop>Featured, the featured levels are my favourite due to the challenging levels you can try out made by people like you, and they've made their levels so good they made it onto the featured. A suggestion I have is that you have more colours to select from, as the only colours are Red, Orange, Blue and Baby blue, I am not offended that there aren't many colours, I also like the fact that you can challenge yourself by setting Strict mode. If you are wanting to get this game but haven't seen the reviews, then I would say that it is a very good  overall ad would recommend this game. Thanks for reading this review, it's a very good game. So i don't usually leave a review, i have prolly over 1000 games at this point and this would be my first review. 
First i would say that i love it and here is why:
1- The game is so polished to perfection and runs perfectly every step is so clean and it helps the player feel the rhythm and give me such a great immersive experience.
2 - The price for me it was 8.50AUD not on sale i have played it for 8.8 hours strait at this point that is less than a dollar an hour, amazing even if i where to stop now i feel i've had my moneys worth, especially considering i've paid more for DLC i never ended up using :(
3 - The music, ok so some of it i find a little meh, but some of it is great, even the ones that a meh are still enjoyable which i consider a big win.
4 - The level design, in all the mainline songs there is a little break down of paths you will be experiencing in the main song as well as a bit of an indication as to how it will sound,like an entrée. Fantastic idea, both exciting and informative.
5 - The community, it seems to me the story is a big tutorial for community levels, the difficulties range from 'Super Jedi God' to 'reasonably hard' and if you are lucky 'kinda relaxing' the not only is there massive scope for skill to develop but the creativity of many of the levels "chefs' kiss" they are so pretty and unusual its just great to see and it makes the level even more enjoyable on top of the already good music.
6 - The make your own level feature, i've only had a quick look at it but i found it surprisingly simple to understand and use, if there was a song i was desperate enough to play i could see myself making my own level for it, provided it couldn't find it anywhere else of course, just knowing that it is there and i could if i wanted to is a really nice feeling.
7 - The precision, it is possible that just getting to the end of the level may not be enough, for the perfectionist there is an option that will see you time every movement perfectly, its extremely satisfying and only made possible by how polished the game is. This offers an exciting 'easy to play, hard to master' dynamic that makes you want just one more round to see if you can get it this time.

Some things I wasn't a fan of - 
1 - I don't mind a convoluted path of progression, however, when the screen pulses to the beat it can be quite disconcerting, as well as a certain level having strait up jitter to deliberately throw you off which is diabolical and visual changes that are very jarring when trying to focus. i know there is a setting to minimise some of the flashing but it doesn't remove or reduce the aforementioned effects. Which is ok, its just frustrating.
2 - Is rage game, comes with rage. this isn't a surprise but its still, maybe play a calming simulator game after this

Some things i would love to see - 
1 - I WANNA DECORATE MY BALLS (i've been itching to say that), i want them custom and exciting some how more connected to me how i want them (lol). there is so much the colour of each of them, the trail, how it explodes.
2 - There is such a large focus on the level and everything that is going on is often very pretty i think it is a shame that there is not a way to save a run and watch it back without the overlays to just appreciate what you have just done and how it all looks. 

The developers have taken a simple concept and made it sparkle and standout though so much fine tuning and effort, and it comes though, like a soft inviting hand on the shoulder. I look forward to any further products and developments.

A geometry-based rhythm game. Sounds cool, right? If you think it doesn't, guess what? It is in fact cool! The unconventional format may throw newer players off, but the more you play, the more you start to recognize common structures, and the better you get at reading levels. (It also helps to know the song for some user-made levels.) For more unconventional rhythms, you may need to work out some math to figure out what the rhythm sounds like. Nothing too advanced, though, just comparing angle measures. The progression of the main levels is pretty good, with slower songs and simple rhythms for beginners ranging to super-hard bonus levels with super fast tempos and even quintuplets. (For those who don't know what quintuplets are, it's a sequence of five notes that together have the same value of four of the same note. You basically never see them in written music.) There's also a fairly versatile level editor for you to make your own levels. Overall, it's a pretty cool game.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

DO NOT GET THIS GAME IF YOU AREN'T WILLING TO PUT IN A LOT OF TIME. Both of my friends that I recommended this game to found it fun for the first hour, but then as the levels got harder they gave up on the game because it was "too hard". This is one of those games where you need to put in a lot of attempts and fails in order to beat a level. But the feeling you get when you beat a level you have spent ages on is worth every penny. So yeah, keep in mind that if you give up easily, this game just isn't for you.
At some points calming, and others infuriating, this game is a perfect balance of skill leading to fun in the game! Highly recommended.

This is one of my favorite rhythm games. It really does train your rhythm (gaming) skills in a unique way combined with cool graphics for what it is. On top of that, the Neo Cosmos DLC ramps things up to 1,000,000% and is one of my all-time favorite DLC's for any game ever.

This is a must-play for any rhythm gamers.

I can't give this game a more glowing recommendation. Please take the time to play this if you have *any* interest in Rhythm games. It's so incredibly cheap and easily my one of my favourite rhythm games I've played. The game's included courses have fantastic music and act as an excellent way to work your way up to some of the challenging player-made courses. The game's also a lot more forgiving than it was at release, with checkpoints having been added to the game's dev-made stages retroactively.

Also the DLC is a really excellent bit of content, but don't touch it 'till you've beaten up to maybe world 10 or 11, it's no joke.
Wow. Just wow. A wonderful game, plenty of room for improving your skills as you play this game. Well made creator levels, bonus dlc, and bonus songs are what really make this a great game.
I sure do feel like a different breed after that!

This game is just incredibly innovative. The way it represents music in geometry is impressive and hard to wrap your mind around at first, but each group of levels slowly teaches you each new pattern until you're forced to put it all together in one final test. This way, very few things in the longer levels felt unfair -- I had seen them before, and knew I knew how to do them, it was just executing them all in a row. 
Additionally, I appreciated how it simplified rhythm games down to one button. I love a lot of rhythm games, but this is one I could give to my younger siblings to play, and they had just as much fun as I did. I'm not saying the game is easy : Its not. I'm saying that its very simple and that the complexity comes from advanced rhythms, level design, and precision. 
Last, I just wanted to say that the music is really nice and that I really appreciate how much the part mirrored in the rhythm you actually play is emphasized so much. It makes it a lot easier to figure out what you should be playing, and then connect the visual pattern you're seeing to a sound, which allows you to then remember the patterns for later and sightread things more confidently. It was just very helpful.

Gameplay is downright simple on the surface:
1) memorize the song
2) tap out the rhythm (any key(s) will do)

GOOD: The balls-bouncing-on-a-track mechanic illustrates syncopated and off-beat rhythms better than a typical falling-notes mechanic does (although I dislike how the VFX occasionally makes learning new songs harder than it needs to be)

BAD: But like any rhythm game, learning songs does boil down to practice and memorization, making any VFX and slick visuals a moot point.  You'll make it through the first handful of levels fairly quickly, but then your progress will slow.

In short, it's a fun rhythm game, good for casual players and with lots of user-created content for the more serious players.

A Dance of Fire and Ice, often abbreviated as ADOFAI, is an interesting rhythm game base off a simple gimmick. 2 balls will spin around one another, needing to follow a path, the path being shaped by the music. While easy to pick up, this game is very difficult to master. The game also contains several gameplay mechanics so that once a map is mastered, you can always challenge yourself more on it. On top of that, ADOFAI also features custom maps that anyone can create and upload to the Steam Workshop. In the end, this is a very good game that I would recommend to anyone that is a fan of rhythm games.

Positives:
-Easy to pickup, hard to master
-Decent replayability
-Custom levels support

Negatives:
-Can't think of any

This is a great and challenging rhythm game for people who have played the odd simple rhythm game but still consider themselves relatively "beginner." It certainly takes some time to adjust to the way rhythm is visualized here but once you do, it becomes an enjoyable game with plenty of obstacles to overcome. Each level builds up your skills slowly as things get more challenging, along with having a short set of tutorials before the main level. This is ideal as you never feel overwhelmed as a player. I discovered this game by chance and decided to give it a shot (definitely try the free version they link to!) and I'm really glad I did cuz it is so much fun. Also, this isn't relevant to the game itself, but for me was a definitive bonus: you can get trans- and enby-coloured balls using special codes! 

My one and only complaint is that practise mode doesn't allow you to go any further than 10 notes or so past where you made it, which can get frustrating if you just want to get an idea of the song all the way through or even just complete a full section nice and slow. Its been a mild irritant, but doesn't usually detract too much from the overall gameplay.

For those who enjoy a challenge and like rhythm games, this is a must. This game is just so good, from the songs and gameplay to the visuals. I just finished all the [spoiler]12[/spoiler] base worlds (not including the bonus ones) and if this game didn't have the custom songs and level builder I would be the saddest person on earth cause I'm really craving for more. Warning, this is a though game and I do have some previous experience with rhythm games and drums so if you're not very good at rhythm games expect a whole lot more than 8 hours to complete the base levels. But the practice routines and modes are there to help you so don't let that get in the way of experiencing this perfect game.

Despite being a rythm game, A Dance of Fire and Ice seems to utilize the same audio system as in for example Friday Night Funkin: it looks like the game uses a premade audio clip consisting of all sounds accompanying clicking, which is being played on top of a song. The results are that there are no audio indications of whether the player clicks in time, too early or too late.

If depending solely on visual cues isn't enough, then the game is not for you.

You also have options such as speed trial to try and beat levels in a speed at which you like which I think is really nice.

And easily accessible custom levels, that's just another plus for the game
It's a very good rythm game where the base levels are fun and good to practice with!

Very enjoyable one button rhythm game. The base tracks and collabs are super fun to play and the DLC provided a heap of additional content for Workshop community and the excellent custom tracks they keep pumping out.

Only gripe with the DLC is the sections where the game becomes platforming rather than rhythm. It was a cool gimmick for around 5 seconds and then became immensely tedious and very frustrating. 

Now that I've completed it, however, I'm going to continue sinking hours into this game. Highly recommended.

All the fun of learning a piece of music, without actually learning an instrument. Simple as can be, you just push a button in time, but somehow enjoyable. 700+ attempts at a stage, and I still don't feel frustrated.

This is a creative take on the rhythm genre, but has a steep learning curve. You will excel if you are skilled at sight reading and pattern recognition. If not, you will find yourself needing to use the practice mode a lot, and lean on memorizing each song, as missing a note is basically an auto fail. 

Not for impatient people with short attention spans (i.e. me). It's not a HARD pass, but there are other rhythm games that satisfy the finger itch while giving you a greater sense of accomplishment.
